// TEST: exec_generic_record
// EXPECT: output "42;hi"
// EXPECT: targets js, ts, python, rust
//
// Generic record (`record Box[T] { value: T }`) codegen: a type-parameterized
// value type, constructed at two distinct instantiations (`Box[Int]` and
// `Box[String]`) and read back via field access.
//
// This is the regression fixture for the Python generics defect (DV12, Python
// slice): `record Box[T]` emitted `class Box:` with a field annotation
// `value: T` and no `T = TypeVar("T")` / `Generic[T]`, so the module raised
// `NameError: name 'T' is not defined` at class-evaluation time, before `main`
// ran. The fix emits `T = TypeVar("T")` once per type parameter (deduped across
// the bundle), adds `Generic[T, …]` to the class bases, and imports
// `TypeVar`/`Generic` from `typing`.
//
// `// EXPECT: targets` deliberately OMITS `go`: Go emits the struct literal
// without its type argument (`Box{Value: 42}` rather than `Box[int64]{…}`), so
// `go build` rejects "generic type Box[T any] without instantiation" — a
// separate, pre-existing Go-backend defect tracked under DV12. The cross-target
// generics work (Go construction-site type-argument inference; TS/Rust generic
// *methods* — a `Box[T]` method body further breaks TS interface-merge and
// Rust `impl<T>`) is a later session; this fixture seeds it. Flip `go` on (and
// add a generic method) once that lands.
//
// The fixture stays to construct-and-read (no method) precisely so it remains
// green on js/ts/rust today, isolating the Python TypeVar/Generic fix.
//
// `main` is intentionally NOT `public` (see hello_world.bock for the Go
// entry-point rationale).
module main

record Box[T] {
  value: T
}

fn main() -> Void {
  let n = Box { value: 42 }
  let s = Box { value: "hi" }
  println("${n.value};${s.value}")
}
